AccordionDetails1.Text: If you’ve applied for an EEF grant for your technology once before but were unsuccessful, you may apply again. BEIS will not consider an application if the technology has already been submitted twice.

govukheadingm.Text: The Energy Entrepreneurs Fund (EEF) supports innovative carbon-reduction technology through capital grants of up to £1 million.

GovMainInfo.Text: The Fund is open to UK organisations of any size, in both the public and private sector. It is particularly focused on helping small and medium-sized businesses, including start-ups.

Header1.Text: Will at least 50% of this project's activities take place in the UK?

Accordion1.Text: How can I tell if my project will take place in the UK?

AccordionDetails1.Text: The United Kingdom includes England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.

AccordionDetails2.Text: This does not include the Isle of Man and the Channel Islands. British overseas territories such as Gibraltar are also not included.

AccordionDetails3.Text: Activities may include, but are not limited, to:

Accordion2Details1.Text: The Energy Entrepreneurs Fund is primarily aimed at UK businesses and organisations.

Accordion2Details2.Text: You must be registered in the UK if you’re:

Accordion2Bullet2.Text: the lead applicant of a partnership ('consortium')

Accordion2Details3.Text: Project partners may be based abroad. However, at least 50% of the project work must take place in the UK.

Header1.Text: Can you match at least 10% of your total project costs?

AccordionDetails1.Text: You must have funding in place to cover a certain percentage of your total eligible project costs. This is referred to as ‘match funding’.

AccordionDetails2.Text: Your minimum contribution depends on factors including your organisation, the type of project work you’ll be doing and how much you’re applying for.

AccordionDetails3.Text: Your match funding contribution may come from sources including bank loans, private investors, friends and family or your money. It may not come from other public funds.

AccordionDetails4.Text: You can find detailed information on match funding in section 5 ‘(Funding levels and subsidy requirements’) of the EEF Phase 9 Guidance Document.

Hint.Text: Learn more about technology readiness levels in the guidance below

Header1.Text: Has your project reached technology readiness level (TRL) 3: proof of concept?

AccordionDetails1.Text: Technology Readiness Level (TRL) is a way of judging the development of a innovation. BEIS uses this system in its assessment process. Your project must be at a minimum of TRL 3 (Proof of Concept) to get an EEF grant.

AccordionDetails2.Text: Projects which have reached TRL3 have ‘proof of concept’. This means that work has been done to prove that an idea can be made into reality.

AccordionDetails3.Text: To prove that your innovation is feasible you should be able to:

AccordionBullet1.Text: your project can be built or developed

AccordionBullet2.Text: results from testing for real-life application

AccordionDetails4.Text: You can find a full guide to TRL in the EEF 9 Guidance Document
